This paper deals with the complexity of finding cliques in random graphs, which is a fundamental problem in computer science. The use of Sum-of-squares hierarchy is a common technique in computational complexity theory, which suggests that the paper could belong to cs.CC (Computational Complexity) or cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The paper also involves the study of random graphs, which could place it in cs.IT (Information Theory) or cs.LG (Machine Learning). Finally, the paper introduces new combinatorial methods, which could make it relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
